\section{Experiments}
\subsection{Experimental Setup}
We evaluate the proposed classical foreground-background harmonization pipeline on a set of foreground-background image pairs collected from the Internet.
Each foreground object is associated with a manually specified binary mask and is inserted into a target background image using a predefined bounding box.
All methods are evaluated under the same placement configuration to ensure fair comparison.
We compare the following variants:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Hard Paste}: direct copy-and-paste without processing;
    \item \textbf{Gaussian}: Gaussian feathering with alpha blending;
    \item \textbf{Poisson}: gradient-domain Poisson blending;
    \item \textbf{Gaussian + Color (Ours)}: Gaussian blending followed by masked Reinhard color transfer;
    \item \textbf{Poisson + Color}: Poisson blending followed by masked Reinhard color transfer.
\end{itemize}
Unless otherwise specified, Gaussian blending uses a kernel size of 15 pixels, and Poisson blending is implemented using OpenCV seamless cloning with the NORMAL\_CLONE mode.
\subsection{Evaluation Protocol with Large Models}
Quantitatively evaluating visual harmonization remains challenging due to its subjective nature.
Traditional pixel-level metrics often fail to reflect perceptual quality, especially for boundary smoothness and color coherence.
Following recent practices, we adopt a large vision-language model (VLM) as an automated evaluator to assess the perceptual quality of composite images.
Specifically, we use a pre-trained large vision language model GPT 5.2~\cite{hurst2024gpt} to score each composite image along the following criteria:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Boundary Smoothness}: whether the transition between foreground and background appears natural without visible seams;
    \item \textbf{Color and Illumination Consistency}: whether the foreground object matches the background in color tone and lighting;
    \item \textbf{Overall Visual Coherence}: an overall assessment of perceptual realism.
\end{itemize}
For each criterion, the model is prompted to assign an integer score from 1 (poor) to 5 (excellent).
The final score for each method is obtained by averaging scores across all test images and evaluation dimensions.
\subsection{Prompt Design}
To reduce ambiguity and improve consistency, we use a fixed evaluation prompt for all methods and images.
An example prompt is shown below:
\begin{quote}
\small
\textit{
``You are given an image created by inserting a foreground object into a background scene.
Please evaluate the visual quality of this composite image based on the following aspects:
(1) boundary smoothness between the foreground and background,
(2) color and illumination consistency,
and (3) overall visual coherence.
Give each aspect a score from 1 (very poor) to 5 (excellent).''
}
\end{quote}
The same prompt is applied to all composite results to ensure consistency across evaluations.
\subsection{Quantitative Results}
Table~\ref{tab:llm_eval} reports the average scores assigned by the large model.
Methods with Gaussian feathering consistently outperform hard copy-and-paste and Poisson blending in terms of boundary smoothness.
Applying masked Reinhard color transfer further improves color and illumination consistency, leading to higher overall coherence scores.
\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\small
\begin{tabular}{lccc}
\toprule
Method & Boundary & Color & Overall \\
\midrule
Hard Paste & -- & -- & -- \\
Gaussian & -- & -- & -- \\
Poisson & -- & -- & -- \\
Poisson + Color & -- & -- & -- \\
Gaussian + Color (Ours) & \textbf{--} & \textbf{--} & \textbf{--} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Large-model-based perceptual evaluation. Scores are averaged over all test images.}
\label{tab:llm_eval}
\end{table}
\subsection{Qualitative Analysis}
\begin{figure*}[t]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{comparison.pdf}
  \caption{Qualitative Comparison of our methods.}
  \label{fig:qualitative}
\end{figure*}
Figure~\ref{fig:qualitative} presents qualitative comparisons.
Hard copy-and-paste produces sharp and unnatural seams.
Poisson blending reduces boundary artifacts but may introduce local color bleeding or contrast distortions near the object boundary.
In contrast, Gaussian feathering provides smoother and more stable boundary transitions.
After applying masked color transfer, the foreground appearance becomes better aligned with the background illumination, resulting in improved overall visual coherence.
\subsection{Discussion}
The evaluation results indicate that, in our classical composition setting, Gaussian-based boundary blending is more robust than Poisson blending.
While Poisson blending enforces gradient consistency, it may over-propagate background gradients into the foreground, leading to undesirable color artifacts.
Masked Reinhard color transfer effectively compensates for global photometric discrepancies without altering background appearance.
Overall, the combination of Gaussian feathering and color transfer yields the best harmonization performance.

